Israel Stocks: Ampal-American, Ceragon, Clal Insurance, Rabintex

-- B y   R o n i t   G o o d m a n
-- 
2011-03-13T16:26:18Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-13/israel-stocks-clal-insurance-delek-automotive-rabintex.html
  Israel ’s TA-25 Index retreated 1.5
percent to 1,243.95 at the 4:30 p.m. close in  Tel Aviv , the
lowest level since Nov. 14. Investors traded about 1.4 billion
shekels ($393.7 million) in shares and convertible securities.  The following stocks rose or fell today. Symbols are in
parentheses.    Ampal-American Israel (AMPL)  Corp surged the most since
October 2009, jumping 16 percent to 7.259 shekels. The owner of
a 12.5 percent stake in East Mediterranean Gas Co. said supply
of Egyptian gas to Israel will resume tomorrow.    Ceragon Networks Ltd. (CRNT)   dropped to the lowest level
since Dec. 1, retreating 6.1 percent to 40.11 shekels. The cost
of computer-hardware parts may increase after the earthquake in  Japan  hurt manufacturing capacity, said Gilad Alper, a senior
analyst at Meitav Investment House Ltd. in Tel Aviv.    Clal Insurance Enterprise Holdings Ltd. (CLIS)   slid to
the lowest since Oct. 7, retreating 3.3 percent to 90 shekels.
The insurance company estimated damages at its Broadgate unit of
about 28 million shekels from the earthquake in Japan.    Delek Automotive Systems Ltd. (DLEA)   fell to the lowest
since Nov. 30, decreasing 3.4 percent to 44.33 shekels. Migdal
Capital Markets Ltd. said it is reviewing its recommendation and
price estimate on the importer of Mazda cars following the
earthquake.    Orckit Communications Ltd. (ORCT)   increased for the
first time in four days, climbing 3.6 percent to 9.744 shekels.
The maker of telecommunications equipment was rated new “buy”
with a 12-month price estimate of $4.50 per share at Roth
Capital Partners LLC.    Rabintex (RABN)  Industries Ltd. (RABN IT) surged the most since
Oct. 28, advancing 25 percent to 0.721 shekel. A unit of the
maker of protective materials received a $14.7 million order
from the U.S. Army.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ronit Goodman in Tel Aviv at 
 rgoodman9@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
